Why Streaming Might Be Failing

The httr2 SSE streaming is relatively new. Possible issues: 1. httr2 version - You might need to update: install.packages("httr2") 2. Network/proxy - Some networks block SSE 3. API changes - Anthropic may have changed SSE format

Check Your httr2 Version

packageVersion("httr2")
# Should be >= 1.1.0

# Update if needed
install.packages("httr2")

Workaround: Use Batch Mode by Default

Add this to your ~/.Rprofile:

# Disable streaming by default for claudeposit
options(claudeposit.stream = FALSE)

Then restart R, and everything will work reliably!

Try the batch mode examples above and let me know if they work. The functionality is identical - batch mode just doesn't show incremental progress, but it's actually more reliable!

User2025-11-29T18:38:04.334Z

options(claudeposit.stream = FALSE) response <- claude_query("What is the difference between lapply and sapply?") cat(response)

Key Differences Between lapply and sapply

lapply - List Apply

  • Always returns a list
  • Output structure is predictable and consistent
  • Each element of the result corresponds to an element of the input
lapply(1:3, function(x) x^2)
# [[1]]
# [1] 1
# 
# [[2]]
# [1] 4
# 
# [[3]]
# [1] 9

sapply - Simplified Apply

  • Attempts to simplify the result to the most appropriate structure
  • Returns a vector, matrix, or array when possible
  • Falls back to a list if simplification isn't possible
sapply(1:3, function(x) x^2)
# [1] 1 4 9  # simplified to a vector

When Each Simplifies Differently

# Returns vectors of different lengths
lapply(1:3, function(x) rep(x, x))
# [[1]]: 1
# [[2]]: 2 2
# [[3]]: 3 3 3

sapply(1:3, function(x) rep(x, x))
# [[1]]: 1
# [[2]]: 2 2
# [[3]]: 3 3 3
# (stays as list - can't simplify)

# Returns same-length vectors
sapply(1:3, function(x) c(x, x^2))
#      [,1] [,2] [,3]
# [1,]    1    2    3
# [2,]    1    4    9
# (simplified to matrix)

Which to Use?

  • lapply: When you need predictable list output (safer for programming)
  • sapply: When you want simplified output for interactive use (convenience)

# File: example_analysis.R

analyze_sales <- function(data, date_col, amount_col, group_col) {
  # Convert date column
  data[[date_col]] <- as.Date(data[[date_col]])

  # Calculate monthly aggregates
  monthly <- data %>%
    mutate(month = format(!!sym(date_col), "%Y-%m")) %>%
    group_by(month, !!sym(group_col)) %>%
    summarise(
      total_amount = sum(!!sym(amount_col), na.rm = TRUE),
      avg_amount = mean(!!sym(amount_col), na.rm = TRUE),
      n_transactions = n(),
      .groups = 'drop'
    )

  # Calculate growth rates
  monthly %>%
    arrange(!!sym(group_col), month) %>%
    group_by(!!sym(group_col)) %>%
    mutate(
      prev_total = lag(total_amount),
      growth_rate = (total_amount - prev_total) / prev_total * 100
    )
}

Now select the function and try: 1. Addins → Explain Selection - Understand the tidyeval syntax 2. Addins → Generate Documentation - Create roxygen2 docs 3. Addins → Improve Code - See suggestions

#' Null Coalesce Operator
#'
#' Returns the left side if not NULL, otherwise the right side.
#'
#' @param x First value
#' @param y Second value (default)
#' @return x if not NULL, otherwise y
#' @noRd
`%||%` <- function(x, y) {
  if (is.null(x)) y else x
}


#' Print Claude Response
#'
#' Pretty-prints a response from Claude with proper formatting.
#'
#' @param response Character string from claude_query()
#' @param width Maximum line width for wrapping (default: console width)
#'
#' @return Invisibly returns the response
#' @export
#' @examples
#' \dontrun{
#' response <- claude_query("Explain dplyr")
#' print_response(response)
#' }
print_response <- function(response, width = getOption("width", 80)) {
  # Process the response to handle escaped characters
  formatted <- response

  # Replace literal \n with actual newlines
  formatted <- gsub("\\\\n", "\n", formatted)

  # Print with cat for proper rendering
  cat(formatted, "\n")

  invisible(response)
}


#' Ask Claude (Convenience Wrapper)
#'
#' Convenience wrapper around claude_query() that automatically formats output.
#'
#' @param prompt Character string with question/request
#' @param ... Additional arguments passed to claude_query()
#'
#' @return Character string with response (invisibly)
#' @export
#' @examples
#' \dontrun{
#' ask("What is the tidyverse?")
#' ask("Explain this code", context = gather_context())
#' }
ask <- function(prompt, ...) {
  response <- claude_query(prompt, ...)
  print_response(response)
  invisible(response)
}


#' Package Startup Message
#'
#' @param libname Library name
#' @param pkgname Package name
#' @noRd
.onAttach <- function(libname, pkgname) {
  packageStartupMessage(
    "claudeposit v", utils::packageVersion("claudeposit"), "\n",
    "Claude Code integration for Posit Workbench\n",
    "Run get_backend_status() to check configuration\n",
    "Tip: Use ask() instead of claude_query() for better formatted output"
  )
}


#' Check Package Dependencies
#'
#' @return Logical indicating if all required packages are available
#' @noRd
check_dependencies <- function() {
  required <- c("httr2", "shiny", "miniUI", "rstudioapi", "jsonlite", "bslib", "cli")

  missing <- character()
  for (pkg in required) {
    if (!requireNamespace(pkg, quietly = TRUE)) {
      missing <- c(missing, pkg)
    }
  }

  if (length(missing) > 0) {
    stop(
      "Missing required packages: ", paste(missing, collapse = ", "), "\n",
      "Install with: install.packages(c(", paste0("'", missing, "'", collapse = ", "), "))",
      call. = FALSE
    )
  }

  TRUE
}


#' Setup claudeposit Package
#'
#' Interactive setup wizard for first-time configuration.
#'
#' @export
setup_claudeposit <- function() {
  cli::cli_h1("claudeposit Setup Wizard")

  # Check dependencies
  cli::cli_alert_info("Checking dependencies...")
  check_dependencies()
  cli::cli_alert_success("All required packages installed")

  # Choose backend
  cli::cli_h2("Backend Selection")
  cli::cli_text("claudeposit supports two backends:")
  cli::cli_ul(c(
    "API: Direct Anthropic API (recommended, requires API key)",
    "CLI: Claude Code CLI (requires separate installation)"
  ))

  if (rstudioapi::isAvailable()) {
    backend_choice <- rstudioapi::showQuestion(
      "Choose Backend",
      "Use Anthropic API (recommended)?",
      ok = "Yes - API",
      cancel = "No - CLI"
    )

    if (isTRUE(backend_choice)) {
      # API setup
      cli::cli_h2("API Setup")
      cli::cli_text("You'll need an Anthropic API key from: https://console.anthropic.com")

      set_api_key(scope = "keyring")

    } else {
      # CLI setup
      cli::cli_h2("CLI Setup")

      if (!claude_cli_available()) {
        cli::cli_alert_warning("Claude CLI not found")
        cli::cli_text("Install from: https://code.claude.com")

        open_url <- rstudioapi::showQuestion(
          "Install CLI",
          "Open installation page in browser?",
          ok = "Yes",
          cancel = "No"
        )

        if (isTRUE(open_url)) {
          utils::browseURL("https://code.claude.com")
        }

        return(invisible(FALSE))
      } else {
        test_cli_connection()
      }
    }
  } else {
    # Non-interactive
    cli::cli_alert_info("Run set_api_key() to configure API backend")
  }

  # Set options
  cli::cli_h2("Configuration")
  options(
    claudeposit.backend = if (exists("backend_choice") && isTRUE(backend_choice)) "api" else "cli",
    claudeposit.model = "claude-sonnet-4-5",
    claudeposit.max_tokens = 4096,
    claudeposit.stream = FALSE  # Batch mode by default for reliability
  )

  # Final status
  cli::cli_h2("Setup Complete!")
  status <- get_backend_status()
  print(status)

  cli::cli_alert_success("You're ready to use claudeposit!")
  cli::cli_text("Try: ")
  cli::cli_ul(c(
    "ask('What is the tidyverse?')  # Formatted output",
    "Addins menu → Claude Chat",
    "Select code → Addins → Explain Selection"
  ))

  invisible(TRUE)
}

After Reinstalling, Use the New ask() Function

Instead of claude_query(), use ask() for automatically formatted output:

library(claudeposit)
options(claudeposit.stream = FALSE)

# Now use ask() instead of claude_query()
ask("What is the difference between lapply and sapply?")

This will automatically format the output with proper newlines!

Or Format Existing Responses

If you already have a response stored:

# Old way (messy):
response <- claude_query("What is dplyr?")
cat(response)  # Shows \n characters

# New way (formatted):
print_response(response)  # Properly formatted!

Updated Examples with Better Formatting

# 1. Data wrangling - beautifully formatted!
ask("
I have a data frame with columns: date, user_id, revenue, country.
I want to:
1. Calculate total revenue per country per month
2. Find the top 3 countries by revenue each month
3. Pivot the result to have months as columns

Show me the dplyr/tidyr code to do this.
")

# 2. Code explanation
code <- "
library(ggplot2)
ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = mpg, y = hp, color = factor(cyl))) +
  geom_point(size = 3) +
  geom_smooth(method = 'lm', se = FALSE) +
  theme_minimal()
"

ctx <- list(selection = code)
ask("Explain this ggplot code step by step", context = ctx)

# 3. Quick questions

ask("How do I handle missing values in dplyr?")
ask("Explain R's S3 vs S4 object systems")

r2 <- claude_query_conversation("Which package for data cleaning?", history = r1$messages)
print_response(r2$response)
